export const batch127 = {
  'discipline-is-destiny-the-power-of-self-control.json': {
    base: { id: 'discipline-is-destiny-the-power-of-self-control', title: 'Discipline Is Destiny', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781615789703 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'There are no easy paths to greatness',
        text: "A young Hercules once stood at a fork in the road. One trail looked soft and welcoming. The other looked rough, steep, and ready to test every muscle in his body. He had to choose. Take the gentle path and stay comfortable, or walk into the hard one and risk becoming stronger.\n\nWe face the same choice most days. We can keep our bad habits alive, or we can build new ones. We can stay in our safe place, or we can step into the unknown.\n\nThe harder path is the only one that makes you grow. It is the only one that changes both your life and the world around you.\n\nGreatness hides on the road most people refuse to walk. You trade comfort for growth, and that is the deal.\n\nStick with this summary if you want Stoic ideas you can use today."
      },
      {
        title: 'Tomorrow is a myth you tell yourself',
        text: "Classical philosophy lists four main virtues: courage, self-control, fairness, and wisdom. Self-control, often shortened to discipline, is the bedrock of reaching your goals and unlocking your potential.\n\nDiscipline is the habit of controlling yourself and avoiding extremes. It is also predictive. The small choices you make today shape the life you wake up into tomorrow. Stick to your routines and you will build a disciplined life. Tell yourself you are not good enough and you will keep putting things off, and that delay becomes your new normal.\n\nTry to see discipline not as a tool for winning, but as a win in its own right.\n\nBuilding discipline means living a life where steady effort feels natural. Each small action adds to the next, and a strong base forms for the bigger things ahead.\n\nA common trap when building self-control is treating your future self like a superhero. We like to imagine that future-you will have endless time and endless energy. That fantasy is the main reason people procrastinate.\n\nAt its core, procrastination is a form of lying to yourself. It whispers that you can keep pushing tasks further down the road. The hard truth is that no perfect moment will arrive when your duties simply disappear.\n\nTo fight this habit, ask yourself three simple questions. First, what am I avoiding? Name the task you keep pushing aside. Notice the reason you avoid it. Are you overwhelmed, anxious, or unsure how to start? Naming the problem pulls it into the light. Second, what can I do right now? Pick the smallest possible action. Even a tiny step makes the work feel less scary and gives you a small win. Third, who said I can do it tomorrow? Question the idea that waiting is fine. Picture what happens if you keep delaying. Ask yourself why tomorrow should be easier, and weigh that against just doing the work today.\n\nRunning through this short checklist clears the fog around your delay habits and points you toward real action."
      },
      {
        title: 'Slow and steady still wins',
        text: "Taking charge of your body means taking charge of your cravings. Those small daily pleasures can quietly block a Stoic life. Here are six simple tips to manage your urges and feed your mind.\n\nAttack the dawn. Writer Toni Morrison said her confidence came alive with the first light of morning. By the end of a long day, the brain feels cloudy from the small stresses that pile up. So start your day early, when your mind is fresh and ready to work.\n\nIt is time to take back control. Picture physicist Richard Feynman in 1949. He felt a small urge to drink, and he made a quick choice to refuse it. He decided that no craving should have that kind of power over him. Whether you want to drop soda, move your body more, or stop eating junk food, taking back control does wonders for your health and your focus.\n\nFocus on the craft. Comedian Hasan Minhaj has been asked if he thought he would be a star. He said he dislikes the question, because it suggests comedy is just a ladder to fame. To him, comedy is about the joy of the work itself.\n\nIf you love what you do, you are already a winner.\n\nEmbrace the challenge. W.E.B. Du Bois once told his daughter to brave the cold bath. Pushing through hard moments builds inner strength. When you hold yourself accountable, you take back your power and give less room to anyone who tries to push you down.\n\nTake it slow but stay steady. Octavian did not rush to become the first Roman emperor. He made patient, careful moves. His guiding idea was festina lente, which means make haste slowly. That pacing helped him reshape Rome from a city of brick into an empire of marble.\n\nManage the load. Finally, remember that you do not need to act invincible. Doing too much wears you out, and even the strongest people need rest to keep going."
      },
      {
        title: 'Hold yourself together',
        text: "Discipline is not only about raw endurance. It is the skill of managing yourself. It is easy to get swept up in excitement or carried by big ambition. It is tempting to chase every passing whim or let your feelings drive. Real discipline is stopping those impulses and holding yourself to a higher line.\n\nIn a world full of noise, the power to focus is a superpower, as Ryan Holiday has put it.\n\nHere are five ways to channel your drive and keep yourself in line. First, keep the main thing in mind. To do meaningful work, you have to learn to say no. You cannot do everything. Real focus means picking what matters most and letting the rest go. Second, simply focus. Beethoven was known for getting lost in deep thought, even at parties. That deep focus, or raptus, was where his best ideas lived. Focus is not something you reach once, as Steve Jobs believed. It is a habit you practice every moment. Third, do your best. In an interview with Admiral Hyman Rickover, a young Jimmy Carter shared his rank at the Naval Academy. When asked if he had always done his best, Carter paused, knowing he could not say yes. Rickover's final question, why not, left a mark. That short exchange was not just a review of Carter's past. It was a quiet lesson in self-honesty and responsibility. Fourth, beware of perfectionism. Churchill once joked that another spelling of perfectionism is paralysis. Aiming high is great, but going too far can backfire. The Stoics taught that everything should be experienced in balance, even your ambition. Do not let the chase for perfect stop you from taking your shot. Getting things done is what matters. Fifth, learn to wait. Patience is a quiet kind of strength. It keeps you from rushing into poor choices or missing the best outcomes. Waiting lets things unfold in their own time and reveals the hidden rewards that come to those who trust the process.\n\nTrue excellence is the courage to admit that you could have done better."
      },
      {
        title: 'Choose virtue over ego',
        text: "Real discipline also means holding yourself to high moral standards. These standards make you a better person, a better friend, and a better teacher for the people around you. How do you become a person who lifts others up? Look at these five Stoic ideas.\n\nReserve your strictness for yourself. Stoics do not push their discipline onto other people. Their self-control is private. Marcus Aurelius aimed his high standards inward. He worked well with imperfect people, noting their strengths and accepting their weak spots as things beyond his reach.\n\nUplift others. As Seneca pointed out, real happiness comes from helping other people grow through your example. You can choose to be a positive presence in your community. By showing patience, steady resolve, and honesty in your actions, you plant seeds of good that can grow. Your effect may not be noticed right away, but that does not matter. What matters is doing the right thing and living with purpose.\n\nBear it with grace. The story of Pastor, a Roman knight who was forced to eat dinner with Caligula, the emperor who had killed his son, shows what real strength looks like. Even in deep pain, Pastor kept his self-control, not because he felt nothing, but out of duty to his other son. True temperance is more than staying calm. It is enduring hard things with dignity, knowing that others are watching and drawing strength from what you do.\n\nHelp others carry their load. Antoninus understood this when he took the throne. He knew that more power came with more demand for giving and self-control. Stoic leadership means showing rather than telling. Be the first to face hard work and the last to claim the prize. Accept the weight of your role and lead by example.\n\nStay humble. Self-control matters most when success tempts you to enjoy yourself or act above others. Staying modest is easy when the stakes are low, but at the height of your power you have to resist feeling superior or chasing distraction. Seneca warned that people in high places must act with even more care, because their choices ripple further.\n\nSuccess should not change you for the worse. It should make you better."
      },
      {
        title: 'Be your own best friend',
        text: "Last but not least, the Stoics want you to be kind to yourself. Yes, even when you are fighting bad habits or breaking old patterns. Even when you are tackling hard tasks and walking through hard times. In all of that, you still deserve a small pat on the back for the work you have done and the distance you have come.\n\nStoic teaching points out that discipline is not about being harsh with yourself. It is about building an inner friendship. Cleanthes, a Stoic philosopher, once saw a man yelling at himself and gently said, you are not talking to a bad man. Seneca also reflected on his own growth by saying he had begun to be a friend to himself. Being kind to yourself is a sign of inner strength.\n\nTrue discipline balances firmness with self-compassion.\n\nWhen Epaminondas, a gifted general, was given a small job overseeing sewers, he did not look down on it. He treated the work with the same care he gave his military campaigns. Plutarch wrote that Epaminondas believed a person earns respect through how they do their work, not what the work is. With honesty and effort, he turned a small role into one of honor. The lesson is clear. Greatness is not in titles. It is in the dignity you bring to your work, no matter the task.\n\nThat same dignity should also shape how you treat yourself. Be kind, and notice that you are trying your best and getting a little better each day. You are not your own enemy. You are your own ally on this road.\n\nBuild yourself up rather than tearing yourself down. That is what friends do.\n\nFailure happens to everyone, and mistakes are part of being human. Even the people you admire have lost their temper, hit the snooze button, slipped into bad habits, or struggled as a partner or parent. If you saw them in those moments, you would not judge them harshly. You would tell them to keep going and remind them of what they have already done. So why not do the same for yourself? A note for readers: the idea of eating the frog, or doing the hardest task first, is often linked to writer Mark Twain."
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts',
        text: "Everyone hits hard times at some point in life. How you show up for yourself in those moments is what matters most. Do you complain and feel sorry for yourself, or do you give yourself a fair measure of kindness, stand up, and try once more? To live a real Stoic life, choose the second path. The road of grit, steady courage, discipline, and calm will bring you the best results. Learn to lead your body, your actions, and your moral choices, and you are on the way to living like a true Stoic.\n\nA few ideas to try. First, practice silence. Spend a little time writing down what you think and see how much you can keep to yourself. Say less than you feel you need to. Second, find your flow. Try different activities, whether hobbies or work tasks, and notice how you feel while doing them. A good activity can give you energy for the tasks you do not enjoy. Third, look into other Headway summaries, like one called Think Remarkable, for more on building grit, grace, and growth.\n\nRead it through to the end?"
      }
    ]
  },
  'disrupt-you-master-personal-transformation-seize-opportunity-and-thrive-in-the-era-of-endless-innovation.json': {
    base: { id: 'disrupt-you-master-personal-transformation-seize-opportunity-and-thrive-in-the-era-of-endless-innovation', title: 'Disrupt You!', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781615867424 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Welcome to the age of disruption',
        text: "In ancient Rome, a clever glassmaker invented a flexible glass called vitrum flexile. He brought it before Emperor Tiberius to show it off. To test it, Tiberius threw the cup to the floor, and it did not break. The emperor grew uneasy about the future. The new material could lower the value of silver and gold, which were used to make drinking cups. Once he confirmed that only the glassmaker knew the secret, he had him killed to protect the old economy.\n\nFast forward to the present, and stopping disruption is far harder. Tools like 3D printing and self-driving cars are putting millions of jobs at risk, and clean energy is reshaping global power. This fast change is called disruption, and it transforms whole industries. Unlike simple innovation, it builds new markets and shifts old ones. Real disruption does not just improve things. It permanently reshapes business and the economy.\n\nDisruption comes for every business. The ones that fail to change fall behind. To grow, companies must lead change, not fight it. Netflix moved from renting DVDs to streaming, which shows how staying ahead of the curve leads to success.\n\nDream big and act now. The present is where progress begins.\n\nWhether you want to start a company or shift your career, this summary will help you use disruption to grow."
      },
      {
        title: 'The links that create value',
        text: "The most common model for understanding disruption is the S curve. New technologies grow slowly at first, then quickly, and finally level off. This theory explains past disruptions, but it does not predict future ones. So companies should expect future shake-ups and stay alert.\n\nHere is a quiet rule. Winning as a disruptor is not about inventing new technology. It is about using existing tools to shake up different fields. Smart businesses catch the wave of disruption and adapt to stay relevant. Look at ride-sharing apps like Uber and Lyft. They used existing GPS and smartphones to reshape how people move, offering a more convenient option than old taxi services.\n\nThose who accept that change is certain stand to gain the most, as Jay Samit has said.\n\nJust as companies have links, so do people. These traits shape who you are and guide what you do. Research and development links mean rethinking how you see the world. You can rewire your thinking to look for big-picture solutions instead of step-by-step fixes. Design and production links shape how you respond to challenges. Picture success and train your mind to handle openings when they appear. Imagine your goal and rehearse it in your head. Marketing and sales links shape how you present yourself. Do not lean on past wins. Stress your potential and what you could do next. Sell your future range, not just your past record. Distribution links teach you to spend your time and energy well. Sort your tasks by importance and combine activities. For example, you could listen to an educational podcast while washing the dishes.\n\nTo change yourself, look at each link, find what holds you back, and make moves to break through those limits. It is like rebuilding a car engine for racing. With the right mindset and a plan, you are ready for the race of your life.\n\nStepping out of your comfort zone is the first move in turning fear and doubt into progress."
      },
      {
        title: 'Do not become a dinosaur',
        text: "The line security robs ambition is more than a saying. Many professionals feel locked in by their steady pay and predictable routine, even when they are tired of their jobs. The longer someone stays in a role they do not enjoy, the more they earn and the harder it is to leave and chase their dream. That cycle creates a false sense of comfort that kills new ideas.\n\nMost people will not risk what they have for a chance at something better. That reluctance comes from an old idea of job security, where workers expected to stay with the same employer for decades and retire on a pension. That model worked in the era of stable companies and pensions, but today, with 401(k)s and no pensions, it no longer fits. If your career covers a narrow band of experience in one company or field, what happens if that field disappears?\n\nDo not let the illusion of comfort kill your drive. Real security only feeds your ambition.\n\nThe fear of change affects more than individuals. It also hits whole companies. Many businesses avoid shaking up their tried-and-true methods, even when the market is calling for change. Think of the scene in Jurassic Park III where Sam Neill and William H. Macy are caught between a T. rex and a Spinosaurus. The Spinosaurus, focused on the T. rex, beats it down, while the humans, who seem small, bring in help and survive. That scene is a perfect metaphor for how small startups often disrupt big market leaders.\n\nBig companies, like dinosaurs, are too busy fighting each other to notice the smaller players. Knowing whether you are the disruptor or the dinosaur is key. If you are competing against disruptors, you might be the dinosaur. The lesson is simple. Be brave in the face of change. Companies that refuse to evolve become fossils. A recent note for readers: a 2024 McKinsey survey found that 65% of organizations are now using generative AI on a regular basis, nearly double the year before."
      },
      {
        title: 'Stand out in a sea of talent',
        text: "Uniqueness and authenticity are valuable in business. Still, people often find that being different does not automatically make them a useful hire. Without a clear work history or specific skills, building practical abilities that set you apart is what matters most.\n\nHalf the battle is won the moment you believe in yourself.\n\nFinding the right job can feel impossible because LinkedIn makes job seekers feel like needles in a haystack. The good news is that it is more hopeful than it looks. One smart move is finding potential employers before they post jobs. This gives you a feel for the talent scene, helps you spot companies with unhappy staff, and gets your resume in early.\n\nAlec Brownstein, a creative marketer, took it further. He used Google ads to target top creative directors by buying sponsored links for their own names. When they searched for themselves, they found his site, which led to two job offers and a Clio award. He spent just six dollars on the campaign. Think outside the box to get noticed.\n\nIf you want a strong career path, do not count on luck and assume your work will speak for itself. Back it up with strong personal branding. Self-promotion matters long before you have proven your worth, and your core values stay the same even through a big career change. So those values can guide you to fulfillment on any new path. To build and promote your brand well, try these key moves. First, keep learning. Take online courses and earn certifications to stay current. Second, build a strong resume. Use action verbs to show drive and results, and treat the resume as a marketing tool. Third, try public speaking. Promote your brand at conferences and pitch topics to event planners often. Fourth, use social media. Blog, post, and share to reach your audience, offering your expertise in an authentic way. Engage with influencers and grab unexpected chances. Fifth, raise your visibility. Post often so search engines pick you up, and create content that defines your field. Sixth, publish articles in major outlets to grow your reach in the industry."
      },
      {
        title: 'Design and look matter',
        text: "Have you ever thought about improving something that already exists? Asics and Nike did not invent running shoes, and Coach was not the first to make handbags. Unlike old-school inventors who chase big research breakthroughs, their success came from building a better version of the same idea.\n\nMany first-time founders believe they have to invent the next big thing to win. Yet even small design upgrades can lead to billion-dollar results. For example, Nestlé Waters North America rebuilt its bottles to use 50% less resin. That move saved millions and cut the company's carbon footprint by 55%.\n\nBalance earning with enjoying life. Do not let the chase for money eat up all your time and energy.\n\nDesign-driven disruption often comes from brand extensions, because people tend to trust new products from brands they already love. Snickers ice cream bars kept the flavor and ingredients that made the candy bar famous, just in a new form. On the flip side, Colgate's frozen meals failed because shoppers could not connect a toothpaste brand with food.\n\nIn today's digital world, disruption can be as simple as rethinking how a website looks and works. Good design shapes how people feel about a product, so a user-first site or app can open the door to success. By focusing on what users need and want, businesses can create more engaging experiences, which builds loyalty and a competitive edge.\n\nTo see this in action, look at the travel industry, one of the first to be reshaped by the internet. In the old days, booking a trip meant calling or visiting a travel agent. Then online travel agencies appeared and let people book their own flights and hotels. By 2010, online bookings had soared past 300 billion dollars. Yet those early sites were not user-friendly, because they were built for travel agents, not regular travelers.\n\nSteve Huffman and Adam Goldstein then founded Hipmunk. It was a clean, easy-to-use platform with a simple search and filters for price, stops, and duration. That consumer-first design quickly made Hipmunk a hit, earning a spot on Time's 50 Best Websites of 2011."
      },
      {
        title: 'The art of the pivot',
        text: "Pivoting can feel like tossing aside something you care about, yet it is a vital step toward reaching your goal. It is not a sign of surrender. It is a search for new ways to win. A full 180 flip is rarely the right call. For most, a few small smart shifts at the right moment unlock real progress.\n\nFor a disruptor, every challenge to the old way is a hidden opening, as Jay Samit has written.\n\nThink of a business as a climber working up a steep and shifting peak. The leader has to keep finding the safest line upward. Data plays the role of map, free of personal bias, showing the smartest route at every step. The climber reaches new heights by trusting those signals. For example, Jeff Bezos trusted data-driven signals to lift Amazon to the top of the e-commerce world. Through steady analysis and patient improvement, he turned every major call into a winning one, building a platform that served what shoppers actually wanted.\n\nPersonal growth moves at its own pace. Be patient, stay steady, and celebrate the tiny wins along the way.\n\nPlenty of firms have wobbled on the edge of collapse, only to pivot and rocket to huge success. If doubt creeps in when plans go sideways, recall Sony co-founder Akio Morita. His first electronic product, a rice cooker, flopped. It burned the rice, and he moved fewer than a hundred units. Rather than walk away, he turned his attention to transistor radios. That bold leap paid off big. Sony's transistor radios sold like wildfire and pushed the brand into the electronics market, laying the groundwork for global growth.\n\nMany young firms die not from bad ideas but from running out of cash before the market clicks. Welcoming change opens the door to fresh chances, pulling businesses out of dead ends and pointing them at profitable routes. Sharp founders know the value of failing fast, running small tests, watching the numbers, and pivoting when the data says so. Welcome change so you can stay nimble, ready for whatever disruption comes next."
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts',
        text: "Like it or not, every career and company faces some form of disruption. To be ready for that, you have to spot problems early and treat them as interesting chances. To build that mindset, you first have to disrupt yourself. Then you will thrive in today's shifting business world.\n\nA few things to try. First, sign up for online courses on new technologies that matter to your field. Platforms like Coursera and Udemy offer courses on AI, data analytics, and other disruptive tools. Second, study how others in your field hit their goals. Find people who inspire you by reading industry blogs, going to conferences, and reaching out. Third, explore extra income streams tied to your field, like side projects, consulting, or online content. Fourth, set aside a fixed time each week to brainstorm and work on new ideas. Treat it like a meeting you cannot miss.\n\nRead it through to the end?"
      }
    ]
  },
  'do-it-today.json': {
    base: { id: 'do-it-today', title: 'Do it Today', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781616147511 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Stop putting things off',
        text: "Have you ever had a big project you knew mattered, but instead of starting it, you watched TV or scrolled through your phone? That is procrastination. It is the art of delaying needed tasks in favor of things that feel good right now. Sometimes it feels easier to do the work tomorrow, but when tomorrow arrives, the task gets pushed again, and the cycle keeps going.\n\nProcrastination makes easy things hard and hard things harder.\n\nBeyond procrastination, other unhelpful habits can quietly slip into your routine. These habits break your focus and get in the way of more demanding work.\n\nMost people fall into these habits without noticing. The good news is that you can break free and start making better choices. In this summary, we will look at ways to beat procrastination, stretch your comfort zone, and break unhelpful habits by creating a supportive workspace for yourself.\n\nStart with a small change and keep building from there. The possibilities are wide open. Let us go."
      },
      {
        title: 'Take charge of your life',
        text: "When you set an activity aside because it did not work out or does not look promising, you often hunt for a reasonable excuse. That excuse feels comforting, like a small shield against blame.\n\nThat relief does not last. Excuses for delaying important work or personal tasks hurt you over time.\n\nImagine a student who leans on an AI tool to finish assignments fast. They put things off, assuming things will be fine. With one hour left before a critical deadline, the AI tool crashes. Unable to finish the task by hand in time, the student misses the deadline and loses a shot at an A.\n\nHad the student started a few days earlier, none of that would have happened. It is a small example, but the same scene plays out every day across countless lives.\n\nStop putting off important projects to have fun. Work now, play later.\n\nHarsh as it sounds, laziness is one of the root causes of delay. When laziness takes over, you start telling yourself things like I am tired, this is a mess, I will finish it tomorrow, and it is my job so I can do it whenever.\n\nOn the surface, your reasons for waiting may sound fine, but always weigh the cost before you act. If working an extra hour or two will free up more time tomorrow, think about doing it. But if a project is genuinely draining you, do not keep grinding just to seem productive. Take a break, then come back to it.\n\nProductivity is not about overworking yourself. There is no single rule for every situation, but it helps to hold yourself accountable and aim to make the best call in the moment.\n\nYou cannot escape the responsibility of tomorrow by avoiding it today, a line often linked to Abraham Lincoln."
      },
      {
        title: 'Use streaks to beat delay',
        text: "Putting things off is older than the printing press. Famous names like Leonardo da Vinci, Herodotus, and Eleanor Roosevelt all left quotes about how delay wrecks output. So it is not just a quirk of the social media age.\n\nIf you had to score yourself from one to ten, with ten being the highest, how often do you stall? If you said one or two, you are doing great. And if you think you stall a lot, do not panic.\n\nInstead of fretting about lost hours, flip the script and do the opposite.\n\nThe opening move is to list the core tasks you need to finish daily, weekly, monthly, and yearly. Then, guess how long each one should take.\n\nFor example, picture a 9 to 5 worker who signs up for a new course. Work, commuting, and daily chores stretch them thin, so the course barely moves forward.\n\nTo fix that, decide how many hours the course needs and when you want to wrap it up. For a 40-hour video course finished in two months, that is about eight hours a week.\n\nNext, scan your current habits. What can you swap for course time? Cutting two weekly movies down to one frees up hours for studying.\n\nAs a final move, log how you spend each day and week. The journal helps you spot time sinks and measure how you are doing.\n\nWriting things down clears your head and locks in the right priorities.\n\nDo not punish yourself for missing a target. Your output will not jump from zero to a hundred in a few days. You will get sharper over time by logging your hours, cutting noise, and noticing where you slip."
      },
      {
        title: 'Cut out distractions',
        text: "Modern gadgets are great because they make life easier. Thanks to smartphones and computers, even people thousands of miles apart can stay in touch. Students log in for online classes, professionals unlock new career options, and businesses grow across borders because of this connectivity. And that is only the start.\n\nLike everything, technology carries a cost. Many people cannot imagine going an hour without checking their phone. That constant pull from apps and the web shortens attention spans, making it harder to focus on important work for long.\n\nIs your phone hurting your productivity? Here are some ways to handle it. First, silence messages, calls, and social media pings while you work. Most devices have a focus mode that does this with one tap. Second, leave chat groups that pull you away and add nothing to your life. Third, think about keeping a separate work phone and laptop. Keep only the apps you need for work on them. That way, you can train yourself to focus and tell work time and personal time apart.\n\nSet clear limits in all areas of your life to protect your output and your peace of mind.\n\nNow that you know how to clear distractions from your devices, what can you do to stay productive? Here are a few tips. First, cut down on small talk, especially when you are working on something hard. Letting yourself get pulled off track can cost you a few extra minutes to get back into focus. Second, set specific times of day or week to check work emails. Checking constantly to see who replied can eat up real work time. Third, take a few minutes away from work to stretch. Instead of picking up your phone, use those small breaks to walk around or grab a coffee. Fourth, clear your workspace. It is hard to focus when your desk is a mess. Fifth, do one thing at a time. Trying to multitask can actually take more time than just doing the work.\n\nA note for readers: a Times Magazine poll found that 84% of people worldwide said they could not go a single day without their phone in their hand."
      },
      {
        title: 'Step away from the desk',
        text: "What should you do when you feel buried under work and have a stack of tasks waiting?\n\nA common move is to keep your head down and grind, hoping to clear the deck before you stop. That move can backfire. Every person has a ceiling on what they can produce, and pushing past it means delivering work that falls short of your best.\n\nIt is poor judgment to keep typing when you cannot give the work your full mind. Step back instead. A pause can be a few minutes or a few weeks, depending on the situation.\n\nPause time lets you look at your work with fresh eyes. You will catch errors you would have missed, and you will come up with sharper ideas for raising the bar.\n\nCare for your life by leaning into what already works and patching what needs attention.\n\nHere is a simple framework for stepping back. First, lean on a productivity app or timer to schedule interval pauses. Second, plan one main task between each pause. Third, do not skip your pauses. Fourth, skip email and social media during the pause, since opening them can drag the break out. Fifth, when you have longer pauses that last days or weeks, use the time to enjoy art or pick up a fresh hobby.\n\nIf you are unsure how many pauses to weave into your day, the Pomodoro Technique offers a clear path. It is a time management method developed by productivity expert Francesco Cirillo in the late 1980s.\n\nThe method slices work into 25-minute blocks called Pomodoros, with 5-minute pauses after each one. After four Pomodoros, you take a longer pause of 20 to 30 minutes.\n\nYou can also search your app store for Pomodoro tools. They can automate the timer and the pause, so you do not have to track anything yourself.\n\nVery little is needed to make a happy life. It is all within yourself, in your way of thinking, a line often linked to Darius Foroux."
      },
      {
        title: 'Welcome the unknown',
        text: "Most people want a rich career, and there is nothing wrong with aiming high. But that strong desire can easily turn into harsh self-judgment when things do not go as planned.\n\nIt helps to find a middle ground. Life rarely unfolds the way you pictured, and that applies to everyone, because no one has it all figured out.\n\nProtect your mental health and aim to live your best life. When one door closes, look for the next one and see what unfolds. Uncertainty is part of life, and you cannot avoid it. The aim is to make sure it does not leave you stuck.\n\nAre you thinking about a career jump but unsure if it will work out? Since you probably cannot see the future, finding a zero-risk option is nearly impossible. The real task is making sure the move is what you truly want and then getting ready to take it.\n\nFor example, if your next move is to start a business, think about saving an emergency fund that covers at least six months before you leave your job. Or you could run the new venture on the side and resign once it pays what you need. Will that path work out? There is no way to know for sure. But by welcoming uncertainty and taking smart risks, you will likely be rewarded when the business takes off. You will also feel good knowing you are doing what you love.\n\nWhen making a career switch, give yourself a soft landing by leaning on skills you already have.\n\nMany people think they have to leave their surroundings to find answers and figure out what they want in life.\n\nHowever, Darius Foroux argues that you do not have to leave your comfort zone to do amazing things. You may be more productive when surrounded by the people and things you love, like family, friends, music, and your neighborhood. In other words, do not follow mainstream advice on autopilot. Do what works for you, whether that means changing your location or starting a new project in the same place."
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts',
        text: "Productivity is a key that opens career doors. Finishing your tasks on time and hitting your main goals will give you more room to explore new ideas and move forward faster.\n\nHowever, it is also important to learn how to rest. Do not just take the five-minute Pomodoro breaks. Try to give yourself full rest days or even full weeks. For example, use your company holidays, request time off, or set aside one day each month to do nothing work-related and just relax. Take your life into your own hands.\n\nA few things to try. First, give up your phone at work for a day and see how productive you can be without it. Second, start each workday with the tasks you want to complete and clear distractions while you work. Third, write down how you spend your work time for a month. Look for patterns and chances to change.\n\nRead it through to the end?"
      }
    ]
  },
  'do-the-work.json': {
    base: { id: 'do-the-work', title: 'Do the Work', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781616238873 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Push past daily resistance',
        text: "Success is not handed to you. Plenty of odds line up against you. Right in the center of those odds sits resistance, the wall that keeps us from getting work done. Resistance is a pushing force that shoves us away, pulls our attention off course, and chips away at our progress.\n\nResistance is the parent of stalling. It nudges us to delay the work that matters most. It is an opponent you have to beat if you want a full and useful life. Its grip on your output cannot be brushed off. You have to study it, learn what wakes it up, and steer it aside so you can finish any project.\n\nResistance, peers, relatives, and plain practical reasoning all throw obstacles in the path of growth.\n\nMany forces try to stop you from doing things, but those forces only hold power over people who hand it to them. Anyone, and we mean anyone, can pick up their work and move on to bigger projects. The question is how. This summary answers that. You will learn how to take control of the forces of failure instead of being trapped by them. You do not have to be a prisoner of failure, because you are strong enough to beat it. You just need the right tools. This advice will help with any creative project, whether you are a writer, a dancer, or an entrepreneur. No matter your goal, if you want to reach a better state and live up to your potential, jump in. We will go from start to finish, but with a fresh angle, the angle of resistance itself.\n\nA note for readers: the bigger your task is, the more resistance you will feel while trying to finish it."
      },
      {
        title: 'The forces that block work',
        text: "As creatives, artists, and entrepreneurs, we face daily distractions that often keep us from working well. These forces take many forms, and the first is resistance.\n\nResistance is a common enemy that keeps us from taking needed action. Anxiety, feelings of being less than others, inaction, dependence on others, distraction, shyness, selfishness, and obsession are common ways it shows up. Activities that stir resistance give up instant pleasure in exchange for steady output, well-being, or good behavior. Resistance shows up in our eating plans, daily workouts, personal growth, and skills training.\n\nThe traits of resistance are these. It is invisible. You can only feel it as an energy flow from work in progress. It is impersonal. It is a force of nature, and it acts objectively. It is sneaky. It will lie, make things up, charm, scare, and push you into ignoring your tasks. It is always effective. It always gets into your head. It is constant. You have to fight a new battle with it every day. It aims to kill. It does not want to hurt or weaken. It wants to end things.\n\nUnchecked raw emotion is the second enemy of creativity, after resistance.\n\nSometimes we make mistakes by listening too much to rational thoughts. We think they help, but since they are self-centered beliefs, they only lead to bad results. Instead, we need to tap into our unconscious mind, not our ego.\n\nFriends and family can also get in the way of our productivity and our wish to change, because they want us to stay the same, which hurts success.\n\nThe odds are not entirely against us. These factors are on our side. First, plain ignorance and even stupidity can help in unusual cases. A creative person has to be confident enough to take on a task while ignoring how hard and demanding it is. Stop overthinking. Just do it. Second, stubbornness beats perseverance. When we are stubborn, quitting does not even cross our minds. Third, blind faith plays a big part in creativity and productivity. Believing in things you cannot see can help. Despite its best efforts, do not let resistance shake that faith. Fourth, passion makes us brilliant at whatever we do. Sometimes fear covers up our love and we think we have lost it, but that is often not true. Fifth, friends and family are there for us. When you are unsure what to do next, lean on the people close to you."
      },
      {
        title: 'Start before you feel ready',
        text: "The lack of a solid plan or the challenge of taking on a project is not why we fail. The enemy of success is the noise in our head that keeps stopping us from reaching our goal. A nagging voice tells us why we cannot do a task or start a project. The problem with that voice is that it hides well, so it is hard to notice. We have to admit it is there before we can find ways to silence it.\n\nIt is also important to avoid getting caught in endless research. Learning new things about a topic matters, but we have to be careful not to cross the line, because too much research can become a wall. Just a quick search, no notes, no underlining, no more thinking or talking about the papers. Let the ideas grow on their own.\n\nLet your subconscious do its work. You can always go back and do a deep study after you have started moving.\n\nCreative art grows from a primal place. New ideas usually start at that raw level.\n\nYes, it is better to be simpleminded than overcomplicated. A bit of intentional stupidity is sometimes better than fake intelligence. We cannot work slowly and reluctantly if we want to do big things. We have to go for the kill right away, or we will not be able to do anything meaningful.\n\nThe lesson is simple. Move fast and on instinct. When you start to doubt and feel like giving up, look at what you have already done and let that push you to do more.\n\nWe often think that if we practice enough, we will be so perfect that we will never have problems with our work, which is not true. It is fine to feel worried or afraid, but try not to let those feelings run the show. When you are scared, keep going. That is the real test of your strength.\n\nWhen it comes to writing, get the outline of your piece onto one sheet of paper. That way, you will not get stuck in the small details. You can see what to work on next instead of spending hours inventing every side character's history.\n\nAnother trick is to work backward. Decide where you want to end up and then figure out how to get there.\n\nWhatever you can do or dream you can, begin it. Boldness has genius, power, and magic in it, a line often linked to Steven Pressfield."
      },
      {
        title: 'Do not underestimate resistance on your path',
        text: "Let us move on to the next step of the project. During this stage, you fill in the gaps in the outline. You can start your research now.\n\nWhat you put into those gaps is your pitch. It helps to be bold and let ideas flow. For example, the movie The Hangover has three acts: lose Doug, search for him, find him. When you fill in that outline, you get Stu's wedding with a dancer, Mike Tyson and his tiger, and the high-stakes run-in with Mr. Chow. Those scenes grip the viewer and feel exciting.\n\nResistance matters a lot at this stage. We have to notice it and respect it, accepting that we can never wipe it out, but we can outsmart it. Outwitting resistance takes the right mindset, especially one that is just as strong.\n\nWe need to stay aware of how our desires shape our lives. Simply put, do not stress over quality. Sometimes hold back from overthinking, because momentum matters. Putting our inner voice to rest and moving forward without fear is key to becoming comfortable with hard tasks. Just make sure you finish something, even if it is rough or imperfect.\n\nIt is also important to understand that ideas do not always come in a clean line. Creative ideas do not usually follow neat logic. We will likely find the plan we want somewhere in the middle or the end of our work. Instead of fighting that, be ready for it.\n\nYou can always carry a journal or a recorder. Capturing ideas helps because you have something to refer back to when you forget.\n\nPlaying back a recording and hearing yourself talk about a great idea you had missed is a huge relief.\n\nThere are two steps in the writing, creating, or idea-building process: action and reflection. Action means putting words down, and reflection means looking at your notes or sketches. Never try to do both at the same time.\n\nOur job is to spot our concept before bringing it to life, not to control every idea that shows up. Our job is to listen for that resonance and find the idea. Ignore the doubts and deliver the concept anyway."
      },
      {
        title: 'The seven principles of resistance',
        text: "At this point, you are about halfway through your project. This stage is tough because you will likely hit a wall that feels unbreakable. To break through, you need to master seven principles of resistance.\n\nFirst, there is an enemy. Society tries to brainwash us into thinking evil is not real. Many of us believe the gloom we feel around us and inside us is just an illusion. That is not true. There is a clear adversary working against us. Recognizing that fact is the first step to getting to the other side.\n\nSecond, resistance is unstoppable. It has a killing intent, like a serious illness. We have to accept that our enemy is clever, adaptable, stubborn, brutal, and devastating.\n\nThird, resistance lives inside us. It is a primary foe. It does not come from managers, competitors, or anyone we see as an enemy. It is our own creation. We carry it in our subconscious.\n\nFourth, we are not the resistance. The chatter and noise in our heads are not our fault.\n\nTo beat resistance, we have to spot its triggers first.\n\nFifth, we have to fight resistance. Imagine resistance is a wild animal. We cannot be nice to it, and we cannot try to negotiate with it. The fight is the only way.\n\nSixth, resistance comes second. Before resistance comes the idea. If we can build a vision strong enough to stir up resistance in us, we can beat the negative voice in our head. Help is the opposite of resistance. Help gives us the push we need to keep going, while resistance gives us many reasons to stop.\n\nWhenever you are in doubt, ask yourself two questions. How badly do I want this? Why do I want it? By the time you answer, you should have found a way to recharge and face the task.\n\nRemember and reignite your passion for the project. Find as many reasons to keep going as you can. Whether your motivation is fame, money, a vision, or the wish to prove yourself, hold on to it to kill the resistance.\n\nA note for readers: in most myths, the hero has a helper, the force of assistance. In Native American stories, that helper is often a totemic animal."
      },
      {
        title: 'Do not let fear win',
        text: "The one thing you can count on is the Big Crash, the one big thing that goes wrong. It should not make you quit. Now you have to go back to being a little stupid, a little stubborn, and a little blind in your faith.\n\nLearn not to take failures or wins personally. Crashes are your chance to look back and grow. Solve the problem and move on. No mistake defines your value or worth.\n\nMany people get tangled in fear. We often fear success so much that we steer clear of the very things that would help us reach it. That trap is resistance's favorite game.\n\nMost of us live two lives: the life we live and the unlived life inside us. Between the two stands resistance, a line often linked to Steven Pressfield.\n\nResistance taints every corner of our lives in ways we cannot see or admit. Its trick is to make us feel exposed and naked. It makes us feel exposed and fools us into believing that if we open up, we will be judged.\n\nNobody wants to be judged or pushed away, so we get scared and let that fear cover up how important the work is. As a result, we do not finish the task. Resistance wins.\n\nWe wreck our own success when we let resistance grow and take over our thoughts and actions.\n\nYou can stop that outcome. Beat resistance at its own game, and you will be free, because once you have beaten it, you know you can do it again. Finish something once, and you will handle that task a million times more easily. No matter how often you stumble, keep moving until you reach your goal. You can get it right as long as you keep checking where you stand. What matters is that you have beaten the enemy and built a new life. You become different, and finishing tasks gets much easier.\n\nStill, do not let your guard down. Remember, resistance never fully goes away. Sooner or later, you will hear its voice in your head. So be ready. And when resistance shows up again, you will have a few tricks ready. Most of all, start again before you feel ready."
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts',
        text: "Take a clear look in the mirror. Will you allow resistance to drag you off your path, or will you set fear down and do the work?\n\nYou are an artistic and creative soul, a real one. The innovator inside you needs a spark to take action. No matter what storms are swirling around you, you have to keep your eyes on your targets. A silent force is trying to push you back, scatter your focus, and keep you from your craft. Pour everything you have into making sure that force does not win. Your success rides on it.\n\nOne thing every successful person shares is hunger. They attack each task with every ounce of energy they can gather. They ignore the soft voice of resistance whispering in their head. They act. Train yourself to act the same way.\n\nWhatever project has been sitting on your shelf, pick it up and start right now, this very moment. Begin with the rough sketch of an idea. There will be time later to polish and fix. Stay open to other voices and learn from people who have walked the road. Shared knowledge cuts through any emotional wall that tries to choke your creativity.\n\nTry this simple exercise. On any project, slice your outline into three acts: the opening, the middle, and the close. A great example sits in Leonardo da Vinci's The Last Supper, which breaks into the table that fills the canvas, the gathering of Jesus and his followers, and the play of perspective lines.\n\nCutting your work into acts shrinks the fear factor. You can also pin your theme to a sticky note on the wall to keep every scene lined up with that theme.\n\nRead it through to the end?"
      }
    ]
  },
  'do-what-matters-most.json': {
    base: { id: 'do-what-matters-most', title: 'Do What Matters Most', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781616324474 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'The power of picking what counts',
        text: "Every single person alive wants to perform well. Most of us dream of moving toward our goals and crossing items off our to-do list.\n\nBeing effective feels good. It creates a sense of progress, and that sense of progress feels like forward motion. The opposite happens when you are buried under a giant to-do list. You freeze. You stall. You feel stuck in thick mud.\n\nThe cleanest way out is simple. Pour your time into the things that matter. Ignore the rest. Do not let a thirty-minute chore eat up three hours because you lost focus.\n\nPutting first things first moves your life in the right direction. The last few years made this lesson more urgent, because the COVID-19 pandemic flipped everyone's plans. People had to work in ways they had never tried. But those who knew how to set priorities and make real progress stayed flexible, and they could roll with whatever came at them.\n\nDo not fall for the empty promise of putting things off. Skipping a task may make today lighter, but it doubles the weight of tomorrow.\n\nSetting priorities clearly makes you a more effective person. For companies, a leader who knows how to prioritize shapes the whole team's success. Output equals profit, and profit is what every business needs. The trouble is, most people do not know where to begin.\n\nThis summary will walk you through three keys that turn you into a more effective person. Following the Shallenberger brothers' advice, you will learn how to sort your time well, covering every role you fill in life. That way, you can move toward bigger goals and become a more effective person across the board. After all, we all want to reach our goals. Small steady steps stop you from ever saying what if."
      },
      {
        title: 'A clear vision, real goals, and a plan unlock productivity',
        text: "Rob and Steve Shallenberger spent decades watching how top business leaders actually work. Their findings revealed that most leaders spend energy on the wrong tasks, while the most important work slips through the cracks or never gets enough time. These findings fueled their first book, Becoming Your Best: The 12 Principles of Highly Successful Leaders. They did not stop there, though.\n\nYou do not need to run a business to chase productivity. Anyone can apply the three strategies in this summary. Leaders shape their team by managing their own time well, but knowing how to be effective helps every person.\n\nThe three steps that can lift your output by 30 to 50% are shaping your personal vision, setting clear goals for each life role, and building a real plan for every week.\n\nA vision matters because it pulls you forward and keeps you on track. Yet, most people cannot name their vision. They feel the urge to move, but they cannot say where or why. What do you want to reach? What is the point of all this? Those questions deserve a real answer.\n\nDrowning in tasks creates stress and worry.\n\nOn top of that, you have to accept that life is not a single role. Every person wears many hats through the day. You might be a parent, a son or daughter, a friend, a leader, an employee, a mentor, and the list keeps going. All those roles matter, and you should not drop one to be effective in another. Too many people do, and that is the root of the home-versus-work balance problem.\n\nBeing effective in every area of life lines your daily work up with your goals. Small steady progress builds a better life. Letting productivity run wild without focus does the opposite and freezes you in place.\n\nA note for readers: research from Fingerprint for Success found that 67% of American employees saw their home and work-life balance improve a lot once they switched to remote work."
      },
      {
        title: 'Working yourself to the bone is not a trophy',
        text: "A false honor comes with overwork. Somehow society treats grinding too hard as a good thing. But a healthy life needs a healthy balance between home and work. Too much work also feeds the habit of putting things off.\n\nHave you heard the phrase task saturation? It means you have piled on too many jobs and run out of time to do them well. You may not have the right resources, which makes everything ten times harder. In that state, stress piles up, exhaustion settles in, and focus slips away.\n\nStress at work wrecks your health, raises the risk of depression and anxiety, and tanks your output.\n\nBurning yourself out is not something to brag about. It does not impress your manager, and it does nothing good for your health or your results. You simply cannot do your best work when you are stressed. If anything, you make more mistakes and end up in conflict with coworkers. The honest truth is that a day has a fixed number of hours, and it is far smarter to use those hours well than to load them so full that you collapse.\n\nThe way to escape the proud-but-burned-out badge that workplaces seem to love is to shift your mindset. Stop trying to cram in as much as possible. Focus on the things that matter most, and train yourself to finish them with steady effort. It is about choosing your actions on purpose each day rather than reacting to whatever shows up. You take charge of your schedule and stick to it, instead of letting your schedule run your life and dictate your mood from morning to night."
      },
      {
        title: 'A personal vision lights the way',
        text: "Most people carry a vague picture of what they want from life, but they never sharpen it enough to take action. They drift through the years, never reaching the dreams they keep talking about.\n\nThe first move toward real productivity is naming your personal vision and seeing it in your mind as vividly as you can.\n\nLook at the most impactful people in history. They all had a clear vision. Names like Gandhi, George Washington, and Martin Luther King Jr. come to mind. They knew what they wanted, picked the one thing that meant the most, and chased that vision in every move they made. That is the path you need to walk. You may not have a vision to change the world, and that is fine. Whatever your vision is, it has to mean something deep to you.\n\nYour personal vision does not have to change the world. It just has to change your world, a line often linked to Rob and Steve Shallenberger.\n\nA vision gives you direction and purpose. The moment you feel the urge to stall, you can pull your vision to the front of your mind and feel the energy to push through. A shared vision can also bind a team at work, pulling everyone toward the same target.\n\nTo uncover your vision, you have to sit down and let your mind wander. Give real thought to what matters in your life and your work. You can build a vision for every role you play, whether you are a parent, a teacher, an employee, or a friend. Find what matters in each role and let your vision grow from there.\n\nYour vision is your own. You can ask people close to you for input, but the vision has to feel deeply personal."
      },
      {
        title: 'Show up fully in every role you hold',
        text: "You can crush it at work and have a rocky relationship with your partner. You can have a great home life and struggle at work. The secret of real productivity is performing well in every area of your life. That does not mean being flawless or hitting 100%. It means giving your best effort. It is easier than it sounds. You only need to name the roles you play and set goals for each one.\n\nIt is easy to drift when you have no target in life. It is like losing your GPS signal with no map. You wander in the dark, with no sense of direction.\n\nGoals move you forward, and they also help you reach the things you want.\n\nNaming your goals takes real thought. Ask yourself what you want to reach in the next 12 months at home and at work. Then ask how you can keep track of the progress you are making in all parts of your life.\n\nThese questions help you start spotting your priorities, and you should give them proper time. Once you set your goals, you have to commit and work at them steadily over time. This kind of soul-searching shifts your mind away from what you cannot do. It points you at the things you can do.\n\nAction without planning is wishful thinking, a line often linked to Antoine de Saint-Exupery.\n\nRun through the goal-setting process for each of your key roles, keeping your vision in mind. Your goals should line up with your vision for each role. Then start writing your goals. Make them SMART, which means they are specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, and time-specific.\n\nOnce you set your goals, share them with people you trust. You are building accountability, which makes it more likely you will stick with them and keep moving. Also, write your goals down and post them where you will see them every day as a steady reminder."
      },
      {
        title: 'Planning turns dreams into done',
        text: "A lot of people skip planning. They think being too structured kills spontaneity, but planning does not mean cramming every second of the day into a slot. Planning lets you focus on the things that really matter and cross them off your list.\n\nRob and Steve Shallenberger recommend pre-week planning. Before the week kicks off, sit down and decide what you need to finish that week. That way, you are not guessing or winging it. You have a clear direction, and you can steer your week where you want it to go.\n\nWhen it comes to performance and productivity, pre-week planning is the keystone, the most important stone in an arch. Pre-week planning is what drives the vision and goals to become a reality, a line often linked to Rob and Steve Shallenberger.\n\nPlanning can feel awkward or tough at first, but it gets easier every time you do it.\n\nWhether you pick a paper notebook or a digital app, it does not matter. It is a personal process you can shape to fit your style. When you run your pre-week planning, make sure that anything you add lines up with your vision and goals. You do not have to make giant leaps every week. Some weeks, the steps will be tiny. Some weeks, you will not move at all. That is fine.\n\nPlanning hands you a sharp sense of control over your time, which lifts your confidence and cuts the odds of stalling.\n\nPick five to seven roles that you need to fill that week, be it an employee, a parent, a son, or a daughter. Then plan your week for each role. If your child has a dentist visit on Wednesday, that is what goes in Wednesday for that role. If you have a client Zoom on Thursday, drop that into your plan under your employee role. It helps to draw vertical columns along the top of your planner for the roles, with the days running down the side, so you can see every role at a glance.\n\nFor the rest of the week, pick action points for each role and get moving."
      },
      {
        title: 'Final thoughts',
        text: "Do What Matters Most teaches you that smart prioritization hands you the reins of control and lets you steer them wherever you want. You can coast along, fretting about missed targets, or you can take charge. You only get a fixed number of hours in a day, so how you use them shapes your whole life.\n\nA clear long-term vision keeps you from lurching from one crisis to the next. That pattern shows up in work and personal lives, again and again. Time flies, and before you realize it, you have not reached anything, or you have gone completely off course. Naming your vision and keeping it close to your heart means you stay on the right road, no matter what happens around you.\n\nGoals help with that, of course, but remember that we all play different roles in life. Do not bury yourself in work and abandon your home life, but also do not chase only fun and skip work. It is about balance, and that is exactly what prioritizing gives you.\n\nThe calm and control you feel from planning your time will make you wonder why you waited so long to start. It is the opposite of staring at a giant to-do list and sliding toward delay. That feeling is crushing. Planning makes you feel calm and fully in charge.\n\nRemember that being burned out and stressed is not normal. We often treat it like a badge, but the truth says otherwise.\n\nA few things to try. First, think carefully about what matters most in your life. What do you want to reach? What would break your heart if you never managed to do it? Second, recall how procrastination feels. It may feel good for a moment, but you will have double the work waiting for you next time. Hold on to that memory and use it as a warning when delay tries to pull you in. Third, always carve out time for yourself. Burning yourself out will not earn you a medal. Your health matters more.\n\nRead it through to the end?"
      }
    ]
  }
};
